1493434793820057600 2022-02-15 11:59:36 +0800 <kixes> 13/ And this is pain that doesn't end once the death sentence is carried out—it is trauma that they will have to carry with them for the rest of their lives.
1493434792222007296 2022-02-15 11:59:35 +0800 <kixes> 12/ It's deeply traumatic to receive execution notices just 1 week before
column2: and be expected to juggle prison visits
column3: breaking the news to other family members
column6: on top of personal mental and emotional anguish.

column1: 1493434790745612291 2022-02-15 11:59:35 +0800 <kixes> 11/ It is horrifying for families to have the spectre of death—which
column2: unlike any other circumstance
column3: can be scheduled down to the minute—hanging over their heads

column1: 1493434789113724928 2022-02-15 11:59:35 +0800 <kixes> 10/ What I've learnt from the families I've worked with is that every person is more than the mistakes they've made. The death penalty regime doesn't recognise that
column2: and it doesn't just punish the individual who was convicted of the offence. It punishes the entire family.

column1: 1493434787079798784 2022-02-15 11:59:34 +0800 <kixes> 9/ This is a soothing message for ourselves because then we don't have to think about it any further. But from what I've witnessed over the years
column2: over multiple death row cases
column3: is that there are so many factors that affect the choices that people make.

column1: 1493434785439821824 2022-02-15 11:59:34 +0800 <kixes> 8/ Many of us find it easier to just brand everyone in prison
column2: and especially on death row
column3: as "criminals" and forget about them. We tell ourselves "if they didn't want to face the consequences then
column4: they shouldn't have done the crime".

column1: 1493434783644647425 2022-02-15 11:59:33 +0800 <kixes> 7/ Ethnic minorities are also disproportionately represented on death row. When we find that a system is repeatedly and disproportionately affecting marginalised communities and vulnerable people
column2: we should really be asking if such a system can really be described as "justice".

column1: 1493434782210228226 2022-02-15 11:59:33 +0800 <kixes> 6/ In my years working on this issue
column2: I have come across cases of people on death row who were struggling with poverty
column5: mental health conditions or psychosocial disabilities.

column1: 1493434780415053826 2022-02-15 11:59:32 +0800 <kixes> 5/ We buy into this narrative so much that it's almost as if it doesn't matter to people that this is not actually supported by evidence.
1493434778703785984 2022-02-15 11:59:32 +0800 <kixes> 4/ We take pride in how relentless and merciless we can be
column2: telling ourselves that we're just being pragmatic and tough and that's why Singapore's streets are cleaner and safer and we are doing better than others.

column1: 1493434776916983809 2022-02-15 11:59:32 +0800 <kixes> 3/ Singapore operates on very punitive logic—we think that if we police more
column2: if we bring in harsh penalties and tell everyone about how "zero tolerance" we are

column1: 1493434775193157633 2022-02-15 11:59:31 +0800 <kixes> 2/ There’s no clear evidence the death penalty is more effective than any other punishment in deterring drug offences. The issues of drug use
column2: drug dependency and the drug trade are complex and can’t be eliminated/"solved" by harsh penalties and sending people to their deaths.

column1: 1493434773502820353 2022-02-15 11:59:31 +0800 <kixes> 1/ Sharing more of the comments I sent @VICEWorldNews:  It's very disappointing that the Singapore government is so determined to continue executions
column2: after zero executions in both 2020 and 2021.
